If you are in the area of West 116 Street and Frederick Douglass Boulevard (Eighth Avenue) you may want to drop by and sample the simple, satisfying fare offered here weekdays from 4 pm to 6 pm. Sign in, sit down and a meal served on a tray will be brought to you by a volunteer. Additional food, fruits and vegetables -- bagels even, are distributed as available. A first-rate "soup kitchen" and one of Harlem's best-kept secrets which has seen a succession of professional ball players and celebrities volunteer their help over the years.

Great resource for people who need food. Very helpful, respectful, non-intimidating, with a friendly feel. Great people helping where help is needed. Very good food pantry, available to all comers. The meals are institutional food, but when you are hungry, food is food. The food pantry has a system which allows people to make their own choices within different categories, more like a little market, less intimidating and more respectful than some other places (I don't mean to speak against food pantries which offer food to the needy - they help out of the goodness of their hearts, but they just don't know how it feels to have to put out your hand). The shoppers at the Food Pantry also help each other, discuss choices, and share suggestions and recipes for what is available. What a good place to have when you are in a bad place!
